	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">joe78 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Just after a good place to find one of these buggers cause here in Australia where I am it's hard to come across NES clone consoles and they usually end up costing more than they're worth.<br /><br />Also if you don't know of a place to buy them, a price estimate would be appreciated also.</div>
<br />
<br />
<br />These chips are made out of pure uncut unobtainium.  The only place to get them that I know of is out of famiclones, unfortunately... and even then 99% of them will have useless gloptops.  The one place where I found usable ones is on those "super8" things that plug into the SNES and have the NES/fami cart connectors on the top.  Kinda spendy, but you DO get a nice famicom connector, NES connector, SNES connector, the NES on a chip, and some other goodies.
<br />
<br />The NOAC in the super8 is a gloptop too, but it's on a removable "carrier" board.  Btw, if you wish to remove it, you must use a heat gun... you cannot desolder the pins of it since there will still be a very fine film of solder left, which will rip the pads off the carrier.  Don't use too much heat or else the PCB will delaminate.
<br />
<br />I have only seen a TRUE NOAC once, and that is inside a game axe.  It's an actual QFP in there!  100 pins, AFAIR.  I dunno if it's the "Crappy" style with the bad sound, or if it's the good style.  The super8 appears to have the good style NOAC in it, incidentally.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


